<Name>Adrian Guzman< /Name>< Date>
1621811907888</Date>
< Rate>
1< /Rate>
< review>
I used to be a regular parishioner at this church along with my family until February of 2019. I was in my second year of confirmation and enjoyed the idea of finishing up. However A friend of mine's mother had died from breast cancer that had metastasized to her brain in January. Suddenly that family of six children found that they had to all live, go to college, and pay all expenses off of the meager wage of a construction worker in California who was not getting his wages because of issues inside of his company. So I decided to ask the church for permission to hand out a flyer with a link to a go fund me for the family and collect some funds from any people who were willing to give it to them at the end of mass in their announcements where they frequently ask for money and donations. They did not answer the phone for three straight days. Eventually on Saturday I decided to go to a vigil which was ironically about helping people in their time of need. The padre who was there that day said that he was not part of the church and could not authorize it but that if he was he would give me his blessing to do so, and was referred to Father Eddie Ruiz. Eddie Ruiz said they he did not have a procedure for this at the church and said he would not allow me to do this because he did not know the family directly through the church. After three days of waiting for a phone call that never came, waiting in the rain while writing an email to him for an hour, and multiple hours of waiting, I got a less than 3 sentence reply denying help to this family after being told to follow the church's example and help people in their time of need. On Sunday I decided to go door to door handing out flyers and learned that about $135 had been given to the family through those means by some strangers. After this I stopped going to the church and didn't return to my confirmation. Set me on a spiritual downwards spiral I'm still trying to get out of. I walked into a church for the first time since then yesterday. To any good soul who reads this, I sincerely hope you think long and hard before giving another donation or prayer at this parish.< /review>

We waited outside in line with about 5 other customers.  Once people would get to the register the next person would wait inside the lobby and stand right inside the door. When the person in front of me approached the register I stepped into the lobby with my fiancee' as everyone before us had done.

We were immediately met with a terrible attitude from someone named Cliff I believe (greenish/yellowish died hair). It was my first time ever seeing him.  It seemed that he was a new manager at this location.  He yelled in a rude/condescending tone "WAIT OUTSIDE!! WE WILL WAVE YOU IN". Afterwards, Josh explained that we were just following what everyone else was doing, Cliff reacted again in a very condescending manner. We stepped out and waited.  Were the first and only customers that I witnessed that had to wait outside until there was  no one checking out at the register.   A few mins later we were waved in by a young lady at the register.

As we walked in, the person waiting in line behind came in as well.  Josh and I waited for the backlash he might receive, but nothing was said to him.  He was allowed to wait inside and order directly after us.  Not only that, but the lady in line behind him, also decided to walk inside.  Once again, no response from Cliff.  I am a black woman, and the only person of color at the store.  My fianc√© and I felt attacked, singled out, and belittled. In this current climate, it became pretty obvious what was happening.  Not only to Josh and I, but from others in the store.

Finally Josh confronted Cliff about his aggression toward us.  He said to Cliff, "I don't appreciate your tone that you are giving us."  And then he asked Cliff, "Why don't your rules apply to anyone else walking in the door?"  Cliff simply responded "If you don't like it, go to another Coffee Bean."

We have over 2500 points on our CBTL app, combined together.  a fair amount of them spent at this location. Id like for the general manager and franchisee to know what type of person is representing their store.  I always felt like I was so proud of my coffee shop that I visit almost daily.  Now I cannot say that I feel that way anymore.  I would hate to see Coffee bean face the same negative coverage that Starbucks faced because of a racist manager.  I will not "go to a different Coffee Bean" as he insisted.  But I will document every visit with my camera until he is replaced with a unbiased manager.<//Text>< Name>
Camille Calvin< /Name>

<text>I really like this place (especially coming from the East Coast where it was all Starbucks and Dunkin) but I do have 3 issues.

1. Most of the flavors are mixed with a cream base. It is interesting but for those that can't handle much in the way of dairy, it is an obstacle. The only flavor that is safe is the vanilla.

2. I really love their sandwiches but instead of using something like a Turbo chef, they use a microwave which leaves the sandwiches not tasting as good as they could.

3. I always see an inconsistency in their drinks no matter what location I go.

I will say that I really enjoy the ambience and they have the best pumpkin flavoring I've had from a cafe establishment.<//text>< gmap_id>

<rate>5</rate>< review>
I just Stopped by there on Wednesday afternoon-ish when I drove back to South Bay from near Mexico and the place was cozy, peaceful, down to earth vibe, clean and  dry/steam sauna and Jacuzzi Were nice. I didn't use bio rooms, warm room etc...thus can't comment on that.
I was so tired from driving, stress from work etc ..requested 1 hour massage (their rate was so reasonable compare to other Spa /massage places) and Never regretted.
The massage guy was an Asian, he was nice, very professional & very easy on the eyes...his skill was phenomenal, satisfying and very soothing/relaxing session made me feel refreshed afterwards. If you expect some kinda happy ending/sexual services from the massage guy, keep looking elsewhere. All he does is just giving the superb massage & I'm totally fine with it. next time I go to the area, I'll stop by this place again just to get a massage from him.
Enjoyed this place much better than other Korean style Spas I visited before in whole LA area.< /review>

< Review>
Prior to VIDA Rescue, I had the experience of trying to go through an adoption process (notice how I said "trying") with another rescue and needless to say, in comparison, I will adopt and recommend to others only VIDA Rescue.

This is the best rescue experience I've had - everything is electronic and they have a simple google survey for you to fill out if you're interested in adoption and it's quick. They also keep their forms updated so you're not filling out something dated 2016.

We set up an appointment to see the available cats and met with Monica. My partner and I told her about what we were potentially looking for (a 3rd cat to be a playmate for our youngest cat so the elder cat can have a quiet retirement) but more so, my partner and I had anxiety about the entire situation in general as introducing another cat could potentially disrupt everyone's routine and most of all, our current cats' behaviors.

Monica was a great listener and answered our questions (no matter how inexperienced it sounded) and instead of us diving right in, she suggested we foster for a month.

Now, it's been less than a month and we made the adoption official. Everything was officiated electronically and done quickly - thank you VIDA Rescue for an amazing adoption experience!< /Review>

< text>
My experience with this facility has been nothing but frustrating. I fell in love with one of their available puppies on PetFinder and filled out an application immediately after it had been posted (assuming I had probably been one of the very first applicants to express interest in this dog). It says on their site that if they don't get back to you within a week or so, it's most likely that the dog has already been adopted. I think this is a very unprofessional way of dealing with a potential adopter. Leaving someone in the dark for up to a week wondering if they're going to get some kind of response or not is very dishonorable in my opinion. I filled out the application last Wednesday and it is now Tuesday. I called the facility five times over the course of the last week to get information on the dog's availability and got no answer and no call-back. I just wanted to get ahold of someone that worked there, but their lack of communication was very stressful to me. I decided to drive out to the rescue to talk to someone face to face. They don't allow walk-ins and meet-ups are by appointment only, so I didn't show up expecting to meet the dog. I just wanted them to know I existed and that I was very eager to possibly meet and adopt this specific dog. I talked to a woman at the front desk and kindly explained the situation. I told them I would appreciate it if they could at least keep me updated on the dog's status, so I left my name and number. This happened yesterday. This morning I refreshed the PetFinder feed and the dog I wanted had been taken down (this typically means they've been adopted). So, the reason I'm writing this negative review is because their total lack of communication was very disheartening from the very beginning. I wouldn't be writing this negative review if they had just taken a few minutes to call me back (or email me) and tell me the dog's adoption was pending so I could move on with my life. Why didn't they just tell me this when I was there in person yesterday instead of keeping me in the dark? I hope the dog went to a good home, but I don't plan on adopting a dog from this facility at this point given the situation. If you fall in love with a dog at this facility, don't get your hopes up! They've probably already found someone else and they will not let you know. I'm extremely disappointed in VIDA rescue, please do better.

EDIT: I may have come off a bit harsh in my initial review for VIDA rescue. I don't think they're a bad shelter, I was just salty about their initial lack of communication after I got my hopes up for a potential adoption. But, I appreciate that the owner of the company expressed sympathy in regards to my experience through reading this review. I'm sorry that they don't have enough staff to stay on top off the influx of applications. I just hope they will be able to come up with a system that will allow them to be more organized/timely about getting back to adopters in the future.<//text>

<Resp>None< /Resp></record></dataset><record>
<name>Frank Desmond</name><user_id>118262310627194529015<//user_id><GmapID>0x80c32a568a03f45d:0xf835545bf13cc6b0</GmapID><Resp>{'time': 1592365311050, 'text': 'Thank you guys for working with us ‚Äî we really appreciate your understanding, and I‚Äôm glad everything has worked out a lot better now!! We heard you guys are now adopting Toby, a little terrier, and crossing our fingers for him! He‚Äôs the sweetest boy; we want to thank you again for choosing rescue and being so kind & understanding.'}<//Resp><Pictures>None</Pictures><Date>1591664632565< /Date>< text>
If you are looking for someplace to adopt a pet, I would highly suggest you find another facility. They are not up front or honest with the information they provide regarding their rescues. For starters, their listing for our now dog said he was 2 years old, however, when we showed up and saw the paperwork, it said he was 4. Not the biggest deal in the world, but why lie about that? Secondly, the paperwork said that he had no behavioral issues. The woman told us that he played happily with other dogs, was good with children and showed no behavioral problems. That also turned out to be a lie. In the 2 months we've owned him, he's growled at my son and bitten him 3 times. To be clear, our son is 7 and would reach out to pet him and get snapped at. He's also charged at and bitten the vet, the groomer, family members, a neighbor, the list goes on. He snarls and growls at children so we just keep him away. We can't have guests over and my son can't invite his friends to play. I understand they want to find pets homes, but that shouldn't be the only goal. The proper goal should be to find a good fit. Had we known he was this aggressive, we probably would have kept looking for a dog that bonded better with children so our rescue can find a more well suited home. It will be more traumatizing to the rescue and heartbreaking for the families to have to return a pet due to aggression or health issues they just can't afford. In addition, she had told us that our dog had seen their vet and had a clean bill of health, however, a day or two later when we noticed his leg was bloody and raw from biting and scratching we took him to a vet of closer to home and learned he had a skin infection that went untreated. When we mentioned it to her, she insisted we see their preferred vet, but after what we found, I wouldn't trust it. We will continue to do all we can for our rescue, however, if he still poses a danger to a home with children, we are going to have to face an emotionally tough and financially costly decision. Find a shelter that is up front and honest with their animals so you know exactly what you are getting into and can make an educated decision that best suits you and your new addition to your family. This place, in my experience, just isn't that place.

UPDATE: Upon seeing this review, VIDA reached out to us and has been more than accommodating and sympathetic to our situation. Unfortunately, in he end, we had to make the very tough decision to surrender our dog. While he is actually a really good dog and won our hearts over, he has some trauma which resulted in aggressive trigger responses that became dangerous for our child. After some discussions with behavioral trainers, the vet, etc. it became evident to us that VIDA may not have seen or known of these aggressive responses during the time they had him in their care.  Maddie with VIDA has been very helpful in taking care of our dog and has been in communication with us to assure us that he is happy, taken care of and most importantly placed in a good home that can better help him heal and grow. Based on their response and communication afterwards, I feel that we all have learned and grown from this experience and I would feel confident in adopting from them again. Thank you VIDA for all of your help and support.< /text>

<Rate>5< /Rate>< text>
I adopted my baby boy Wolf from VIDA and they were SO helpful! They drove him all the way up from Mexico for me to meet and adopt him. The woman who fostered him was a true angel. She bought him from a homeless drug addict who was abusing and starving him, giving the man all the money she had just so she could save Wolf from his terrible existence. She fed and bathed him, loved and petted him and helped him not to suffer anymore. He still had fleas when I adopted him and when I told Laura (the head of VIDA) about it she offered to buy the flea medication to treat him. When I informed her I had already had him dipped and bought medication for him on my own, she took $50 off the adoption fee to cover the cost. This is a wonderful organization with amazing fosters and volunteers. Donate, volunteer or adopt from this rescue. ‚ù§Ô∏è</text>

< review>
On 01/07/2019 evening around 7:30, my wife found a ferret with white color fur roaming at the front door  while she was taking the trash out. She was a bit scare about this type of animal and called for my help loudly, then I rushed towards the front door and saw this ferret was roaming around trying to get into my house. I gently approached this animal with a flash light and discovered it was tamed and friendly.Since it was already dark and cold outside. I decided to take the ferret in and kept indoor overnight. Next morning at 8:45, I called the VIDA and talked to Laura about this stray ferret  if she could accept this ferret. Amazingly, Laura was so kind and friendly, saying that there will be someone coming in later at 9:30 to look after it. She also explained to me where to put the cage on the table in front of the office premise. Wonderful place for animal rescue ! Thanks to all volunteers.....< /review>

<rating>5</rating>< review>
Golden west Collision center has been around a long time. I have had many cars, and many car repairs performed by Golden West. The best thing about Golden West is its culture. Joe, and his staff are very friendly, and easy to interact with. This quality makes it easy to do business with them. Body work is an art form, the car will never be the same as when it rolled off the assembly line, but golden west does a good job getting as close to perfect as possible. Overall, I have been extremely happy with this body shop. I feel comfortable referring anyone who needs this type of work done to them, because I know they will be treated well, and golden west will make it a point to ensure they are happy.

Here is a photo of my car after Golden west repaired it. It was side swiped on the right side, and both the front and rear doors needed to be painted, and the right rear wheel needed to be replaced.<//review>

I had one of THE most terrible experience at Golden west collision. They were very un professional, did not respect schedule, delivery date. < Review>
The hospital in Glendale, CA is not bad, but just for a two hours emergency visit, they charged my SSI recipient mother's Medicare, and Medical and then they sent us an additional bill. They want to collect as much as possible even after charging Medicare and Medical. Then, a few weeks later, we took my mom for a routine mammogram, they took her Medicare and Medical cards again. Charged as much as possible and then sent another bill for that.
Anyway, I try to call them, they kept me waiting with the answering machine saying that they are busy with others. Apparently, so many others have also billing questions and they do not have enough staff to respond to billing questions. They kept sending us two more times by threatening that this is a final notice before they send the bill for collection.
It seems that they are really good at billing and collection after all. So Sad! I will try to not take my mom there anymore.< /Review>

<rating>5< /rating>< review>
I had a triple heart bypass surgery procedure last August 17, 2018
at Glendale Adventist Hospital and remained in the hospital for the next 9 days.  Everyone from the surgeons, nurses, the technicians including the people who brought my meals to my room and the cleaning staff were all courteous in a natural and yet still professional manner. Each one of them made by recuperation much easier.  Recently in April, 2019 I had two stent artery placement procedures surgery done at Glendale Adventist. Once again, all staff members made my overnight stay comfortable and relaxed. The natural caring compassion from the staff begins at the reception /registration desk and continues to the end of my stay in which the hospital volunteers deliver me to my medical van transportation in a wheel chair.  Yes, Glendale Adventist Hospital easily deserves a 5 star rating.</review>

Honestly, I was originally hesitant on delivering there because a few years ago 2 of my friends gave birth there and they were unhappy with the staff. But I must say, something has definitely changed at Adventist because every single person was great for the most part. Every nurse had a charge nurse who came and introduced themselves and asked me to let them know if I was unhappy with anything. Everyone was helpful and nice. The only thing I can think of to say is, I don‚Äôt ever remember a lactation consultant coming by. The nurses were very helpful in the postpartum room, but I would have liked for a visit from a lactation consultant maybe early in the morning, and I believe I was asked about it later on in the evening. I appreciate Glendale Adventist‚Äôs rules about their visitors, they are flexible and accommodating to bigger families and that‚Äôs wonderful! <user_name>Gregory Firth</user_name><rating>5< /rating>< review>
I've had a couple surgeries there with overnight/next day recovery on the patient floors.  The surgical support staff are top notch professionals with may years of experience.  This is serious stuff and I would rather be here than anywhere else for surgery of any type.

On the floor, you have three tiers of nurses assigned to each patient who are busy but good about answering calls.  Food varies from very good to not so good. Temperature controlled room can be set for patient's comfort.  Leg compressors to prevent blocking an artery in the calf - these are assiduous but necessary.  The bed some will like and some will not.  No satellite radio, lousy TV.  Still you are there to get on your feet not watch CNN.

Quality of care is very high.  The ability of nurses to relate varies, but there are many who find the time to go beyond the technical's and provide heartfelt care (Lily and Shampoo - you know who you are).

Gratitude to everyone.</review>

4</Rate>
<Text>I went in to Glendale Adventist for my annual mammogram and bi-annual bone density.  While I generally feel like it is a very good hospital, although my experience there has fortunately been limited, I feel like they need to update their procedures a little. I have been to other women's imaging centers in the past where mammogram results are given immediately, and if other procedures are needed such as an ultrasound, they are also done right away. I have spoken with my doctor about this, but there doesn't seem to be anywhere in Glendale that provides this service. For such a large metropolitan area, this seems a bit ridiculous. I waited 6 days to get my letter in the mail. For most women, the annual  mammogram is fairly stressful, and if a repeat visit is required, it is even more so.  This process needs to be streamlined. This important annual check should be much less stress and hassle.

The other issue I have is with the parking at the outpatient center. I had my tests originally scheduled on a Wednesday morning at 11:00, and when I got there, I could not get a place to park. I followed other cars (I kept seeing the same cars going around in circles) looking for spots for 25 minutes in the parking garage, then finally decided I had to reschedule.  I went at 8:00 in the morning the 2nd time when I was able to get the tests done. If parking isn't available, parking stubs should not be dispensed or there should be readily available overflow. I won't be going there again at any time except first thing in the morning.<//Text>< Pictures>
None</Pictures>

I'm actually very suprised that I got treated with respect here by the majority of the staff, nurses and doctor who attended me. I came in for multiple reasons but one of them was because of my type 2 diabetes, I apparently am eating way too little as I am doing my best to diet and lose weight and well, I had my blood sugar drop down to 58 when I should be around 90 to 140, the doctor was able to help me get it up to about 89 which was the best they could do with very little time, they did lab work on me as well as a CT Scan for my other issue, unfortunately The second problem was sort of a no explanation as the lab work came back normal and my CT scan looked clear of any abnormalities. The level of neglect at this hospital towards a person suffering from chest pains was astonishing.  My uncle was transferred to the hospital from a different hospital due to chest pains. < review>
Okay so no one wants themselves or their loved ones to be in the hospital BUT if that's the case, this is place you'd want to be. My mom had to be transferred here from Bakersfield for a complicated emergency surgery. It was a terrifying experience for all of us but the staff was just stellar (I couldn't even think of a good enough adjective to describe their bedside manner). They were so attentive and kind. Not even just the nurses alone, the doctors, receptionists, the cleaning crew, physical therapists, everyone. You can tell these people really care it's so comforting knowing your loved one is in good hands. Thanks Dr. Badr, Danny, Dr. Habashy, Madeline  (I wish I could remember everyone's name to thank them). But seriously, you guys and girls are literal angels.< /review>

<review>I came into the ER in great pain, but I was treated with respect from the moment I checked in. Immediately after checking in, I was ushered into a small room, where my vitals were checked. Afterwords, I was told to wait in the waiting area until there was a bed available for me.  I did not have to wait very long.  Following that, a nurse visited me and I told him about my reason for coming to the ER. I had a chest E-ray and blood drawn. I later saw the doctor who prescribed medication that I needed to relieve my pain. After a few hours, I was sent home with all test results given to me so that I could take them to my primary care doctor for follow-up the next day. It was an excellent experience, despite my fears and pain.</review><userid>117593933982518660776</userid><Response>None<//Response><Gmap_id>0x80c2c10b06f8c3c9:0xd71f5ee5c2347add<//Gmap_id><name>Miriam Malabel</name><rating>5</rating><pictures>None</pictures><date>1612918369687</date></record></dataset><record>

Sona Minasyan<//Name>
<Pictures>None<//Pictures><resp>None</resp><gmap_id>0x80c2c10b06f8c3c9:0xd71f5ee5c2347add<//gmap_id>< Time>
1523841971638<//Time>
< Text>
They deserve negative 1000 stars. The level of this hospital's incompetency is unbelievable.
My father has liver cancer, cirrhosis, ascites, and diabetes. His ascites was pretty bad; there was a lot fluid accumulated in his abdomen, which was causing chest pain, shortness of breath, and nausea. I called the ER to make sure they could perform paracentesis before taking my father there. The girl (who never introduced herself) on the phone told me that it is something they CAN do. So, we arrived to the ER at 6 p. m. yesterday. The doctor, Nicholas Abram, told us that they couldn't do paracentesis at the ER, so he would get my father admitted so that a specialist can do the procedure at the hospital. He and the nurse told me several times that they would make sure that the procedure is done first thing the next morning (they acted like the doctor made several phone calls to make sure the procedure happens). The only reason why we stayed overnight is the fact that we were promised that the procedure would definitely get done. The ER doctor, by the way, was very unfocused the whole time; he was literally falling asleep in front of my eyes. I even overheard him asking the nurse what day it was when filling up some paperwork (again, this was late in the afternoon).
I went home to get some sleep around 11 p. m. I got a call from the nurse, Stephanie, around 2 a. m. who told me that my father had been admitted and that they would perform paracentesis in the morning, but she didn't have the exact time. I went to the hospital around 7 a. m. today. First of all, I was shocked when my father told me they had given him Tylenol as a pain reliever. People with cirrhosis are not supposed to take any medication that contains Tylenol because it's very bad for the liver. I brought this to the other nurse's attention (Rachel) who said, "OK, I'll make a note." Really? Are you that "smart"? Why should I tell you this? Why are you not aware of this?
Rachel told me that the doctor in charge, Ahn (the spelling might be wrong) contacted a GI that should be coming to do the procedure, but there was no specific time again. Couple of hours later Rachel came back stating that, apparently, the GI can't do the procedure, so they need to find a different doctor. Finally, around 10 a. m. they sent the nurse in charge, Avery, who told me that they need a radiologist to do paracentesis and that radiologists are only available from Monday-Friday, so they can't do the promised procedure today. I can't explain how mad I was at that point. I couldn't believe it. So, they kept my father there for over 20 hours for no reason. I told Avery that this was unacceptable, but she only apologized by saying that the ER doctor wasn't supposed to make any promises and that there was absolutely nothing they could do. I was obviously very mad and increased my tone because the whole situation was simple ridiculous. Another nurse approached me at that point and told me to lower my voice because I was disturbing the other patients. Wow, that's so great you are worried about other patients! I wish my father was treated the same way.
Not only did they not help my father, they made his condition even worse by giving him unnecessary stool softeners that caused him so much pain that he was literally yelling. At that point, we just left the hospital. I couldn't trust bunch of incompetent medical personnel any longer.
After we left, I got a call from Doctor Ahn, who started making excuses about how the hospital had to make budget cuts, which resulted in not being able to perform paracentesis at the ER or having radiologists available during the weekends.
Bottom line, these people wasted 2 days just to charge my father's insurance. Honestly, I don't have any other logical explanation to this whole mess. They could've simply told me from the very beginning that they didn't have the ability to help my father, and would just take him elsewhere.
If you really care about your health, do yourself a favor and avoid this joke of a hospital at all costs.</Text>
